  "doi": "10.1172/jci88165",
  "title": "A \"hotspot\" for autoimmune T cells in type 1 diabetes.",
  "journal": "The Journal of clinical investigation",
  "year": 2016,
  "authors": "Stadinski BD, Obst R, Huseby ES."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examines an insulin-reactive TCR implicated in type 1 diabetes, revealing how a single TCR achieves cross-reactivity with pathogen-derived peptides by focusing binding interactions on a limited \"hotspot\" region within the peptide. The research demonstrates that autoimmune T cells recognize insulin through selective engagement with specific peptide residues, a principle that enables these cells to also respond to structurally distinct microbial antigens. This finding is significant for understanding type 1 diabetes pathogenesis, where molecular mimicry between pathogenic epitopes and self-insulin likely drives initial TCR activation of autoreactive clones. The results suggest that TCR specificity and cross-reactivity patterns can be predicted from standard protein-interaction principles, offering potential strategies for identifying which pathogens might trigger autoimmune responses and for engineering TCRs with controlled specificity profiles.",
